238
00:09:57,475 --> 00:09:58,934
I have the kids.
I am taking care of them.

239
00:09:59,018 --> 00:10:00,478
-[PHONE RINGS]
-They still have all their limbs.

240
00:10:00,562 --> 00:10:02,937
-MOSKOWITZ: Joel Maisel's office.
-I stepped up, I'm here.

241
00:10:03,021 --> 00:10:04,939
-Oh, and I'm not?
-No, you're not.

242
00:10:05,023 --> 00:10:07,150
-You're in Florida.
-What are you implying?

243
00:10:07,234 --> 00:10:09,068
-That you're in Florida.
-How dare you?

244
00:10:09,152 --> 00:10:10,653
MOSKOWITZ: Oh,
Mr. Maisel, a call for you.

245
00:10:10,737 --> 00:10:13,281
-Can you take a message?
-It's about the liquor license.

246
00:10:13,365 --> 00:10:16,034
I have to go. I'm sorry. I am.

247
00:10:16,118 --> 00:10:17,744
-Wait, Joel…
-Yes?

248
00:10:17,828 --> 00:10:21,371
I appreciate you making
sure they have all their limbs.

249
00:10:21,455 --> 00:10:22,789
It's the least I can do.

250
00:10:22,873 --> 00:10:25,585
There aren't that many. Bye.

251
00:10:27,211 --> 00:10:28,754
[SIGHS]

252
00:10:28,838 --> 00:10:30,506
-Hello.
-BRIAN: <i>Joel Maisel?</i>

253
00:10:30,590 --> 00:10:31,798
Brian Miller. I'm calling

254
00:10:31,882 --> 00:10:34,301
in reference to your
application for a liquor license.

255
00:10:34,385 --> 00:10:36,264
What's the problem now?
You need my blood type?

256
00:10:36,348 --> 00:10:36,512
No.

257
00:10:36,596 --> 00:10:37,930
-My firstborn?
<i>-No.</i>

258
00:10:38,014 --> 00:10:39,680
Ethan, pack your bags.
You got a new daddy.

259
00:10:39,764 --> 00:10:42,350
No. Mr. Maisel, I'm just calling
to apologize for the mix-up.

260
00:10:42,434 --> 00:10:44,477
<i>Your application landed in the wrong bin</i>

261
00:10:44,561 --> 00:10:45,895
<i>at the Chinatown office.</i>

262
00:10:45,979 --> 00:10:47,480
<i>We just didn't realize who you were.</i>

263
00:10:47,564 --> 00:10:49,941
Oh. Who am I?

264
00:10:50,025 --> 00:10:51,734
Just know it's all been sorted out.

265
00:10:51,818 --> 00:10:53,319
And your license has been fast-tracked.

266
00:10:53,403 --> 00:10:54,946
You should have it
by the end of the week.

267
00:10:55,030 --> 00:10:57,531
-Okay.
<i>-If you need anything else,</i>

268
00:10:57,615 --> 00:10:59,533
please don't hesitate to call.

269
00:10:59,617 --> 00:11:01,619
Thank you.

270
00:11:04,204 --> 00:11:07,040
-We got the license.
-How?

271
00:11:07,124 --> 00:11:09,876
-I don't know. Luck?
-Luck?

272
00:11:09,960 --> 00:11:12,170
Yep. Felt wrong just saying it.

273
00:11:12,254 --> 00:11:14,589
[SIGHS]

274
00:11:14,673 --> 00:11:16,423
What's the line on the Yankees game?

275
00:11:16,507 --> 00:11:18,008
Yanks minus one and a half.

276
00:11:18,092 --> 00:11:20,010
Minus one and a half.

277
00:11:20,094 --> 00:11:22,012
-Who's pitching today?
-Whitey Ford.

278
00:11:22,096 --> 00:11:24,139
Whitey Ford, sure. Is he good?

279
00:11:24,223 --> 00:11:26,141
-He's pretty good.
-How's he feeling?

280
00:11:26,225 --> 00:11:28,352
Been sick lately?
There's this flu that's going around.

281
00:11:28,436 --> 00:11:30,479
-I wouldn't know.
-Okay, so if you were

282
00:11:30,563 --> 00:11:33,274
to put 20 bucks that you
really needed on the Yankees,

283
00:11:33,358 --> 00:11:35,108
what do you think?
Seem like a good bet to you?

284
00:11:35,192 --> 00:11:36,568
It's not my job to advise.

285
00:11:36,652 --> 00:11:38,444
-Just between friends.
-We're not friends.

286
00:11:38,528 --> 00:11:40,446
Say we were and I was asking.
What would you say?

287
00:11:40,530 --> 00:11:43,042
I'd say you shouldn't be
friends with your bookie.

288
00:11:43,126 --> 00:11:43,533
Thanks.

289
00:11:43,617 --> 00:11:47,161
And maybe you should learn baseball.
Just a tip, pal.

290
00:11:47,245 --> 00:11:48,580
You ever worry people
might not be so scared of you

291
00:11:48,664 --> 00:11:50,206
if they saw you drinking
a liquidated tutu?

292
00:11:50,290 --> 00:11:53,208
-Mayday, Mayday, Mayday.
-I'll be right back.

293
00:11:53,292 --> 00:11:56,003
I'm only staying till I reach the cherry.

294
00:11:56,087 --> 00:11:57,796
[BERNIE PANTING]

295
00:11:57,880 --> 00:11:59,798
Ooh. Ah, I'm nauseous.

296
00:11:59,882 --> 00:12:02,217
-I can't breathe.
-Calm down, Bernie.

297
00:12:02,301 --> 00:12:05,345
I ran here. From Sardi's to here.

298
00:12:05,429 --> 00:12:07,347
-That's 40 blocks.
-And two avenues.

299
00:12:07,431 --> 00:12:10,100
-What's the problem?
-We lost the theater.

300
00:12:10,184 --> 00:12:11,976
How do you lose a thousand-seat theater?

301
00:12:12,060 --> 00:12:13,477
They got a better offer.
They gave it away.

302
00:12:13,561 --> 00:12:14,854
They can't give it away. You booked it.

303
00:12:14,938 --> 00:12:16,897
-You gave them a check.
-Yeah, well, they gave it back.

304
00:12:16,981 --> 00:12:18,107
They gave it back, and you took it?

305
00:12:18,191 --> 00:12:19,942
-What was I gonna do? Duck?
-Fucking yes!

306
00:12:20,026 --> 00:12:21,193
They handed me the
check, I took the check.

307
00:12:21,277 --> 00:12:22,236
This is what civilized people do.

308
00:12:22,320 --> 00:12:23,821
This isn't civilized people.

309
00:12:23,905 --> 00:12:26,032
-This is Broadway.
-Can we push the opening?

310
00:12:26,116 --> 00:12:27,658
No. Gavin's got some pirate movie,

311
00:12:27,742 --> 00:12:29,160
and Sophie's touring in the fall.

312
00:12:29,244 --> 00:12:30,785
-We open now or we don't open.
-What am I gonna

313
00:12:30,869 --> 00:12:32,621
tell the investors?
I left them at Sardi's.

314
00:12:32,705 --> 00:12:34,664
-They're just sitting there.
-Tell them we'll get a theater.

315
00:12:34,748 --> 00:12:36,374
-How?
-Let me worry about that.

316
00:12:36,458 --> 00:12:37,917
If they get wind of
this, they'll back out.

317
00:12:38,001 --> 00:12:39,044
They're not gonna get wind of anything.

318
00:12:39,128 --> 00:12:40,712
Just aim your ass in another direction.

319
00:12:40,796 --> 00:12:42,589
-But I…
-Just go.

320
00:12:42,673 --> 00:12:44,466
Let me figure this out.

321
00:12:44,550 --> 00:12:45,884
Shit.

322
00:12:45,968 --> 00:12:47,969
[PENCIL CLATTERS]

323
00:12:50,638 --> 00:12:52,598
-I need a theater.
-Sure. No problem.

324
00:12:52,682 --> 00:12:55,017
-Like a peekaboo theater?
-What's a peekaboo theater?

325
00:12:55,101 --> 00:12:56,810
-It's a dirty theater.
-A titty theater.

326
00:12:56,894 --> 00:12:58,729
You call a dirty theater
a peekaboo theater?

327
00:12:58,813 --> 00:13:00,314
I got a kid. She listens to calls.

328
00:13:00,398 --> 00:13:01,899
Okay, no. I need a Broadway theater.

329
00:13:01,983 --> 00:13:04,568
-A legit Broadway theater.
-Oh, boy. Tough.

330
00:13:04,652 --> 00:13:06,944
It's a good season this year.
Theaters are booked.

331
00:13:07,028 --> 00:13:09,030
I have a client in this play.
The owners just gave the theater

332
00:13:09,114 --> 00:13:11,032
-to someone else.
-Did you pay?

333
00:13:11,116 --> 00:13:12,950
Yes, we paid. We gave them a check.
They gave it back.

334
00:13:13,034 --> 00:13:14,952
-And you fucking took it?
-The producer did.

335
00:13:15,036 --> 00:13:16,371
He's, you know, "civilized."

336
00:13:16,455 --> 00:13:17,538
This is Broadway.

337
00:13:17,622 --> 00:13:19,332
Guys, please. I need this.

338
00:13:19,416 --> 00:13:21,376
If I don't find a place,
the show's kaput.

339
00:13:21,460 --> 00:13:23,711
I think we can help.

340
00:13:23,795 --> 00:13:26,422
-Really?
-We know some guys.

341
00:13:28,048 --> 00:13:30,384
-Hold on. There.
-[THUDDING]

342
00:13:30,468 --> 00:13:32,386
Better?

343
00:13:32,470 --> 00:13:34,554
-No. What'd you do?
-I fixed the runner.

344
00:13:34,638 --> 00:13:36,473
-What runner?
-Weren't we trying to fix the runner?

345
00:13:36,557 --> 00:13:38,016
-What for?
-To get it to run.

346
00:13:38,100 --> 00:13:39,726
-No.
-Then what the hell were we doing?

347
00:13:39,810 --> 00:13:41,895
-Reattaching the ring.
-What ring?

348
00:13:41,979 --> 00:13:44,897
Worst Abbott and Costello bit ever.

349
00:13:44,981 --> 00:13:46,148
What you got?

350
00:13:46,232 --> 00:13:48,234
MEI: Big box of new records.

351
00:13:51,279 --> 00:13:52,697
Still all Chinese.

352
00:13:52,781 --> 00:13:54,323
This one's Thai.

353
00:13:54,407 --> 00:13:55,908
Oh, good, so I'll know the words.

354
00:13:55,992 --> 00:13:57,910
-You want a beer?
-Nope.

355
00:13:57,994 --> 00:14:00,663
Archie. Come on. Have a beer.

356
00:14:00,747 --> 00:14:03,832
-Let's celebrate.
-Celebrate what?

357
00:14:03,916 --> 00:14:07,252
The liquor license has been
approved and is on the way.

358
00:14:07,336 --> 00:14:08,670
That's great.

359
00:14:08,754 --> 00:14:12,090
Wow. Joel Maisel, king of the clubs.

360
00:14:12,174 --> 00:14:15,301
-But how?
-Must have been my powers of persuasion.

361
00:14:15,385 --> 00:14:17,929
-Right. Or?
-No idea.

362
00:14:18,013 --> 00:14:21,056
Out of the blue, some guy
calls, says there's been a mix-up.

363
00:14:21,140 --> 00:14:22,683
Said they didn't know who I was.

364
00:14:22,767 --> 00:14:24,685
Oh. Who are you?

365
00:14:24,769 --> 00:14:26,687
I'm the guy who now has a liquor license.

366
00:14:26,771 --> 00:14:29,398
-[CHUCKLES]
-Magically.

367
00:14:29,482 --> 00:14:32,401
Hey, Arch, would you go get us some beer?

368
00:14:32,485 --> 00:14:34,403
-We have beer.
-Some more beer?

369
00:14:34,487 --> 00:14:36,572
Are we expecting a crowd?

370
00:14:38,574 --> 00:14:41,451
Okay.

371
00:14:41,535 --> 00:14:43,953
I will go get some beer.

372
00:14:44,037 --> 00:14:46,789
Great.

373
00:14:46,873 --> 00:14:49,000
-Any specific kind?
-It's a fake beer run, Archie.

374
00:14:49,084 --> 00:14:51,503
[CHUCKLES]: Right. Be back soon.

375
00:14:55,215 --> 00:14:57,632
-Thought you weren't a magician.
-Hmm?

376
00:14:57,716 --> 00:14:59,551
You don't seem that
surprised I got the license.

377
00:14:59,635 --> 00:15:01,344
I'm generally unflappable.

378
00:15:01,428 --> 00:15:03,180
You have anything to do with it?

379
00:15:03,264 --> 00:15:05,224
-[SPEAKING CHINESE]
-In English, Mei.

380
00:15:08,644 --> 00:15:10,604
I knew it.

381
00:15:10,688 --> 00:15:13,899
You asked your brother or your cousin

382
00:15:13,983 --> 00:15:15,692
or your cousin's cousin
to push it through.

383
00:15:15,776 --> 00:15:17,193
My cousin's cousin would be my cousin.

384
00:15:17,277 --> 00:15:19,069
Not if you were related
through different…

385
00:15:19,153 --> 00:15:20,613
No, you're trying to distract me.

386
00:15:20,697 --> 00:15:21,864
Who cares how you got it?

387
00:15:21,948 --> 00:15:23,365
-You can't do that.
-Why?

388
00:15:23,449 --> 00:15:26,202
Because I have to do this. Alone.

389
00:15:26,286 --> 00:15:29,246
I don't want you doing me favors

390
00:15:29,330 --> 00:15:32,416
or asking for favors or making
a brisket for the liquor guy.

391
00:15:32,500 --> 00:15:34,667
-Making a what?
-I don't want your help with this.

392
00:15:34,751 --> 00:15:37,545
Hey, John Wayne, if you haven't noticed,

393
00:15:37,629 --> 00:15:39,422
this is a very insular neighborhood.

394
00:15:39,506 --> 00:15:41,758
You can't get anything done
if you don't have cousins.

395
00:15:41,842 --> 00:15:43,176
-I have cousins.
-Chinese cousins, Joel,

396
00:15:43,260 --> 00:15:44,803
or you at least have to know people.

397
00:15:44,887 --> 00:15:46,137
Great. I'll get to know people.

398
00:15:46,221 --> 00:15:48,097
How? Charades?
You don't know the language.

399
00:15:48,181 --> 00:15:50,642
-I'm fucking great at charades.
-Is this pride?

400
00:15:50,726 --> 00:15:52,060
Is that what's happening here?

401
00:15:52,144 --> 00:15:55,062
Maybe it is, but I'm doing
things square this time.

402
00:15:55,146 --> 00:15:57,439
What is "this time"? What was last time?

403
00:15:57,523 --> 00:16:00,526
-This is my business, Mei.
-Fine.

404
00:16:00,610 --> 00:16:03,362
I wash my hands of the whole situation.

405
00:16:03,446 --> 00:16:04,780
-Great.
-Or I would,

406
00:16:04,864 --> 00:16:06,198
if your bathroom water was running.

407
00:16:06,282 --> 00:16:08,492
Plumber's coming tomorrow.

408
00:16:08,576 --> 00:16:11,577
-How do you know the plumber?
-How do I know the license guy?

409
00:16:11,661 --> 00:16:12,912
How do you know the license guy?

410
00:16:12,996 --> 00:16:14,998
[SPEAKING CHINESE]

411
00:16:20,462 --> 00:16:22,463
I did not order these.

412
00:16:22,547 --> 00:16:26,425
[SPEAKING CHINESE]

413
00:16:26,509 --> 00:16:29,178
-Happy?
-Extremely.

414
00:16:29,262 --> 00:16:32,472
[SPEAKING CHINESE]

415
00:16:32,556 --> 00:16:36,393
Ah, see, that I understood perfectly.

416
00:16:42,399 --> 00:16:44,317
[DOOR CLOSES]

417
00:16:44,401 --> 00:16:47,821
-Had it. I've had it.
-Oh, calm down, Martha.

418
00:16:47,905 --> 00:16:49,321
I'm tired of this shit.

419
00:16:49,405 --> 00:16:50,990
-He drags us all the way out here…
-Hi.

420
00:16:51,074 --> 00:16:52,992
-Hi.
-Turn around, little girl.

421
00:16:53,076 --> 00:16:54,785
-What? Why?
-Hey, Martha,

422
00:16:54,869 --> 00:16:57,037
this is what he does.
Don't take it personally.

423
00:16:57,121 --> 00:16:58,789
-He threw food at us.
-He missed.

424
00:16:58,873 --> 00:17:00,165
He fired us, Carole.

425
00:17:00,249 --> 00:17:02,710
Hey, if I had a nickel for
every time Shy fired me,

426
00:17:02,794 --> 00:17:04,545
I wouldn't have to work for Shy anymore.

427
00:17:04,629 --> 00:17:07,338
I'm done walking on eggshells
because he's in a mood.

428
00:17:07,422 --> 00:17:10,008
You want to see a mood?
I'll show you a mood.

429
00:17:10,092 --> 00:17:11,843
He's a fucking star.

430
00:17:11,927 --> 00:17:14,804
Suddenly, you all forgot what
a pain in the ass Elvis was.

431
00:17:14,888 --> 00:17:16,306
Yeah, Elvis would throw food at you,

432
00:17:16,390 --> 00:17:17,974
but at least he'd buy you a car.

433
00:17:18,058 --> 00:17:19,559
What is going on?

434
00:17:19,643 --> 00:17:22,270
Shy showed up as Maria Callas today.

435
00:17:22,354 --> 00:17:24,480
-You want a ride?
-Where?

436
00:17:24,564 --> 00:17:25,814
Back to the hotel.

437
00:17:25,898 --> 00:17:28,191
Shouldn't I at least say
hello so he knows I came?

438
00:17:28,275 --> 00:17:30,485
Not unless you want to get
cocktail sauce on that outfit.

439
00:17:30,569 --> 00:17:31,945
I don't, actually.

440
00:17:32,029 --> 00:17:34,489
Hey, Carole, you've got the damn keys.

441
00:17:34,573 --> 00:17:37,200
[SIGHS] You sure you don't want a ride?

442
00:17:37,284 --> 00:17:40,121
No, I'm… I'm fine. Thanks.

443
00:17:55,844 --> 00:17:57,386
This yours?

444
00:17:57,470 --> 00:18:00,681
Yes, I've been looking for that. Thanks.

445
00:18:00,765 --> 00:18:04,559
Nice boat. Modest. Understated.

446
00:18:04,643 --> 00:18:06,728
Didn't you hear?
Nobody wants to be around me today.

447
00:18:06,812 --> 00:18:08,438
Oh, no, I heard.

448
00:18:08,522 --> 00:18:11,024
It's gonna be a quiet set for
you tonight without a band.

449
00:18:11,108 --> 00:18:13,693
My son's a whiz at the kazoo.
Should I give him a call?

450
00:18:13,777 --> 00:18:15,195
The hell is that?

451
00:18:15,279 --> 00:18:18,073
Never been invited to
a party on a boat before,

452
00:18:18,157 --> 00:18:21,241
and I don't like to come
empty-handed, so meet Fred.

453
00:18:21,325 --> 00:18:24,203
[CHUCKLES] No one's ever
bought me a plant before.

454
00:18:24,287 --> 00:18:26,914
Well, he gets seasick,
so don't get too excited.

455
00:18:26,998 --> 00:18:28,791
It's not much of a party now.

456
00:18:28,875 --> 00:18:31,710
Plenty of food, plenty
of booze, no people.

457
00:18:31,794 --> 00:18:34,254
I'm here, and Fred.

458
00:18:34,338 --> 00:18:36,632
He's funnier when you
get a few drinks in him.

459
00:18:36,716 --> 00:18:38,258
Permission to come aboard?

460
00:18:38,342 --> 00:18:41,094
Sure. Why not?

461
00:18:41,178 --> 00:18:44,078
["PLEASE DON'T MONKEY WITH
BROADWAY" BY FRED ASTAIRE PLAYS]

462
00:18:45,474 --> 00:18:47,392
<i>♪ All the streets are being dressed up ♪</i>

463
00:18:47,476 --> 00:18:50,937
<i>♪ So before they ruin
Broadway, I suggest that you go ♪</i>

464
00:18:51,021 --> 00:18:53,314
<i>♪ To the city fathers and say, "Whoa!" ♪</i>

465
00:18:53,398 --> 00:18:57,068
<i>♪ Glorify Sixth Avenue, and
put bathrooms in the zoo ♪</i>

466
00:18:57,152 --> 00:19:00,696
<i>♪ But please don't monkey
with Broadway… ♪</i>

467
00:19:00,780 --> 00:19:02,864
-FRANK [OVER PHONE]: <i>It's done.</i>
-Really? You sure?

468
00:19:02,948 --> 00:19:03,289
Absolutely.

469
00:19:03,373 --> 00:19:05,075
I mean, it was touch
and go there for a minute.

470
00:19:05,159 --> 00:19:07,285
-Half a minute.
-They were testing a smoke machine,

471
00:19:07,369 --> 00:19:08,954
so they couldn't see
us too good at first.

472
00:19:09,038 --> 00:19:10,872
Once that smoke cleared though, boom.

473
00:19:10,956 --> 00:19:11,460
What'd you say?

474
00:19:11,544 --> 00:19:13,125
FRANK: <i>A little of
this, a little of that.</i>

475
00:19:13,209 --> 00:19:15,043
It turns out we knew a
few guys on the crew.

476
00:19:15,127 --> 00:19:16,919
-They blocked the exits.
-That really helps, you know,

477
00:19:17,003 --> 00:19:18,546
when you don't have to run after them.

478
00:19:18,630 --> 00:19:19,341
Sure, I get that.

479
00:19:19,425 --> 00:19:21,590
But in the end, we just
explained the situation.

480
00:19:21,674 --> 00:19:22,800
Real nice.

481
00:19:22,884 --> 00:19:23,926
There's no need to be rude.

482
00:19:24,010 --> 00:19:25,970
And, eventually, they
saw our side of things.

483
00:19:26,054 --> 00:19:29,306
Bottom line: it's yours.
Good price, immediate occupancy,

484
00:19:29,390 --> 00:19:31,600
and they threw the "Julie" in for free.

485
00:19:31,684 --> 00:19:34,186
We also got you a
period-perfect kitchen set.

486
00:19:34,270 --> 00:19:36,396
-We know those guys, too.
-You know all the guys.

487
00:19:36,480 --> 00:19:39,399
I love <i>Miss Julie,</i> by the way.
Who'd you get to play Jean?

488
00:19:39,483 --> 00:19:42,193
-Gavin Hawk.
-Oh, he's good, very good.

489
00:19:42,277 --> 00:19:43,737
We saw him do the Scottish play.

490
00:19:43,821 --> 00:19:45,655
Listen, I can't thank you guys enough.

491
00:19:45,739 --> 00:19:48,366
You can, actually, and will, eventually.

492
00:19:48,450 --> 00:19:51,327
Okay. Message received,
but either way, opening night,

493
00:19:51,411 --> 00:19:53,204
there are two tickets
for you, front and center.

494
00:19:53,288 --> 00:19:55,914
Opening night, gee.
I… I haven't been to an opening night

495
00:19:55,998 --> 00:19:58,208
since de Mille got us those <i>Oklahoma!</i>
tickets.

496
00:19:58,292 --> 00:19:59,585
You worked for Agnes de Mille?

497
00:19:59,669 --> 00:20:02,504
Yeah.
Brilliant, but could she hold a grudge.

498
00:20:02,588 --> 00:20:04,548
You'd be surprised how
much theater work we do.

499
00:20:04,632 --> 00:20:06,467
Well, thanks again, boys.
You've saved my life.

500
00:20:06,551 --> 00:20:08,635
No problem, Susie. Break a leg.

501
00:20:08,719 --> 00:20:11,055
-Or call us, we'll do it for you.
-[BOTH LAUGH]

502
00:20:11,139 --> 00:20:12,638
You guys kill me.

503
00:20:12,722 --> 00:20:14,515
-One day.
-[BOTH LAUGHING]

504
00:20:14,599 --> 00:20:16,100
[LAUGHS]

505
00:20:16,184 --> 00:20:19,395
-It never ends.
-No, it doesn't.

506
00:20:19,479 --> 00:20:21,439
["ON A SLOW BOAT TO
CHINA" BY KAY STARR PLAYING]

507
00:20:21,523 --> 00:20:23,775
<i>♪ I'd like to get you ♪</i>

508
00:20:23,859 --> 00:20:27,779
<i>♪ On a slow boat to China ♪</i>

509
00:20:27,863 --> 00:20:30,697
<i>♪ All to myself ♪</i>

510
00:20:30,781 --> 00:20:32,992
<i>♪ All alone ♪</i>

511
00:20:35,077 --> 00:20:37,746
<i>♪ Get you and keep you ♪</i>

512
00:20:37,830 --> 00:20:40,207
<i>♪ In my arms evermore… ♪</i>

513
00:20:40,291 --> 00:20:43,543
We're running low. Ooh!
Only 30 bottles left.

514
00:20:43,627 --> 00:20:46,755
Oh, we'd better slow down then.

515
00:20:46,839 --> 00:20:49,173
You know, I have to say,

516
00:20:49,257 --> 00:20:51,383
Fred is having a really nice time.

517
00:20:51,467 --> 00:20:53,969
Good. I was wondering.
He was looking a little green.

518
00:20:54,053 --> 00:20:57,098
Mm, leave the comedy to me, kid.

519
00:20:57,182 --> 00:20:59,350
[CHUCKLES] Agreed.

520
00:20:59,434 --> 00:21:00,684
-Cheers.
-Whoo!

521
00:21:00,768 --> 00:21:04,522
-This is glorious.
-The boat?

522
00:21:04,606 --> 00:21:06,398
No, this sandwich. Where's the fat?

523
00:21:06,482 --> 00:21:09,192
This man cuts corned beef like
my mother's standing over him.

524
00:21:09,276 --> 00:21:11,319
We got lucky. It's a beautiful day.

525
00:21:11,403 --> 00:21:13,404
So why the mood earlier?

526
00:21:13,488 --> 00:21:16,241
Ah, we're having such a nice
time; you want to bring that up?

527
00:21:16,325 --> 00:21:18,701
Come on. Girl trouble?

528
00:21:18,785 --> 00:21:19,953
Why would you say that?

529
00:21:20,037 --> 00:21:21,663
Well, Monica hasn't been around.

530
00:21:21,747 --> 00:21:24,290
-Monica?
-Isn't Monica your lady friend?

531
00:21:24,374 --> 00:21:27,292
Monica is this year's lady friend.

532
00:21:27,376 --> 00:21:29,128
Nice girl, but…

533
00:21:29,212 --> 00:21:31,004
-Not a keeper.
-No, not a keeper.

534
00:21:31,088 --> 00:21:33,048
What about you, Mrs. Maisel?

535
00:21:33,132 --> 00:21:35,634
-Are you actually a Mrs. Maisel?
-Yes,

536
00:21:35,718 --> 00:21:39,596
and no, and yes again,
though, eventually, no.

537
00:21:39,680 --> 00:21:41,890
I've had a lot of champagne.
Translate, please.

538
00:21:41,974 --> 00:21:46,561
I was a Mrs. Maisel,
and then we broke up,

539
00:21:46,645 --> 00:21:49,147
and then we un-broke up,
and then we got divorced,

540
00:21:49,231 --> 00:21:50,606
and then we got remarried,

541
00:21:50,690 --> 00:21:52,775
and now we're filing for divorce again.

542
00:21:52,859 --> 00:21:54,068
Not sure what's confusing you.

543
00:21:54,152 --> 00:21:55,570
You still love him?

544
00:21:55,654 --> 00:22:00,366
Oh, now, Shy, you never
ask a girl "How old are you?"

545
00:22:00,450 --> 00:22:03,577
Or "How much do you weigh?"
or "Do you love your ex-husband?"

546
00:22:03,661 --> 00:22:04,786
[CHUCKLES]

547
00:22:04,870 --> 00:22:06,538
How about you? You ever been married?

548
00:22:06,622 --> 00:22:08,498
Me? No.

549
00:22:08,582 --> 00:22:10,917
I've been on the road since I was 16.

550
00:22:11,001 --> 00:22:12,460
You don't want a family?

551
00:22:12,544 --> 00:22:14,462
I got Reggie. Reggie's my mother,

552
00:22:14,546 --> 00:22:17,007
my father, my brother, my jailor.

553
00:22:17,091 --> 00:22:18,675
You've been friends for a long time.

554
00:22:18,759 --> 00:22:21,052
-Forever.
-[CHUCKLES]

555
00:22:21,136 --> 00:22:22,678
Yeah, forever.

556
00:22:22,762 --> 00:22:25,931
I know sometimes he feels
like an overpaid babysitter,

557
00:22:26,015 --> 00:22:28,767
but I really need him around.

558
00:22:28,851 --> 00:22:31,604
Susie's sort of my Reggie,
without the overpaid part.

559
00:22:31,688 --> 00:22:35,316
I can tell you this much, Reggie
would be mad as hell right now.

560
00:22:35,400 --> 00:22:36,942
'Cause you fired your whole band?

561
00:22:37,026 --> 00:22:39,445
No. He's used to that.
He'd lose his mind seeing me on this boat.

562
00:22:39,529 --> 00:22:41,362
Isn't it your boat?

563
00:22:41,446 --> 00:22:43,781
I'm under strict orders not
to take it out of the harbor.

564
00:22:43,865 --> 00:22:45,867
-You're kidding.
-He doesn't want me on boats

565
00:22:45,951 --> 00:22:48,119
or motorcycles or bicycles
or surfing or walking

566
00:22:48,203 --> 00:22:49,913
or crawling or near kids who sneeze.

567
00:22:49,997 --> 00:22:52,415
It's nice to have someone
looking out for you.

568
00:22:52,499 --> 00:22:56,628
You know… we flipped a coin

569
00:22:56,712 --> 00:22:59,129
to see who got famous first.

570
00:22:59,213 --> 00:23:02,257
-I guess you won.
-Nope. I lost.

571
00:23:02,341 --> 00:23:04,718
Reggie insisted we go two out of three.

572
00:23:04,802 --> 00:23:08,597
-And then you won.
-Maybe. I think Reggie fixed it.

573
00:23:08,681 --> 00:23:10,098
Why?

574
00:23:10,182 --> 00:23:12,142
'Cause he knew it had to be me.

575
00:23:12,226 --> 00:23:15,395
See, Reggie can handle anything.
Life couldn't beat him.

576
00:23:15,479 --> 00:23:20,691
Me, if I wasn't Shy
Baldwin, I don't know.

577
00:23:20,775 --> 00:23:22,736
I don't know who I'd be.

578
00:23:24,404 --> 00:23:25,655
Tell me something.

579
00:23:25,739 --> 00:23:27,531
What?

580
00:23:27,615 --> 00:23:29,451
Is your real name Shy?

581
00:23:32,329 --> 00:23:34,413
-No.
-What is it?

582
00:23:34,497 --> 00:23:36,790
Even Reggie doesn't know that one.

583
00:23:38,834 --> 00:23:40,710
Do you like being famous?

584
00:23:40,794 --> 00:23:44,714
I didn't like not being
famous, so this is better.

585
00:23:44,798 --> 00:23:47,634
I think I'd like being famous.

586
00:23:47,718 --> 00:23:50,137
I think you're gonna find out.

587
00:23:53,432 --> 00:23:56,309
Boy, it's beautiful out here.

588
00:24:01,272 --> 00:24:03,190
POOL BOY: Susie Myerson. Phone.

589
00:24:03,274 --> 00:24:04,942
Thanks, kid.

590
00:24:06,903 --> 00:24:11,073
-I remember the face.
-Ah, get out of Florida.

591
00:24:11,157 --> 00:24:13,533
-Yup.
-Why do I hear splashing?

592
00:24:13,617 --> 00:24:16,536
Sophie. Nice to hear from you.
You loving your new theater?

593
00:24:16,620 --> 00:24:18,579
Got you a hell of a
dressing room, didn't I?

594
00:24:18,663 --> 00:24:19,831
Yeah, the mice seem to like it.

595
00:24:19,915 --> 00:24:21,624
Well, it was good
enough for Julie Andrews.

596
00:24:21,708 --> 00:24:24,043
Well, she's young.
I bet she hasn't drunkenly banged

597
00:24:24,127 --> 00:24:26,212
the light guy thinking
it's her leading man yet.

598
00:24:26,296 --> 00:24:28,756
So you sound good and normal.

599
00:24:28,840 --> 00:24:30,216
Even though everything's gone to hell?

600
00:24:30,300 --> 00:24:32,009
Okay, what's the problem?

601
00:24:32,093 --> 00:24:34,261
Gavin has been talking
and talking and talking

602
00:24:34,345 --> 00:24:35,679
to me for hours.

603
00:24:35,763 --> 00:24:37,639
-That's called rehearsal.
-No.

604
00:24:37,723 --> 00:24:39,599
In addition to the rehearsal talking,

605
00:24:39,683 --> 00:24:42,144
there's been one-on-one,
close-quarters talking,

606
00:24:42,228 --> 00:24:44,021
and I don't know what
the hell he's saying.

607
00:24:44,105 --> 00:24:45,522
I don't know if you realize this,

608
00:24:45,606 --> 00:24:47,107
but he has some sort of accent

609
00:24:47,191 --> 00:24:49,650
that makes normal words
sound completely distorted.

610
00:24:49,734 --> 00:24:51,193
<i>If I hadn't read the play,
I wouldn't have known</i>

611
00:24:51,277 --> 00:24:53,070
<i>-his name was Jean.</i>
-It's not that thick an accent.

612
00:24:53,154 --> 00:24:54,822
I don't know if he's
asking me to fuck him

613
00:24:54,906 --> 00:24:56,615
or if he needs some
water or a cough drop.

614
00:24:56,699 --> 00:24:58,200
Who cares? He's a great actor.

615
00:24:58,284 --> 00:25:01,162
Do we know that, though?
How do we know that?

616
00:25:01,246 --> 00:25:02,204
Read the <i>Times.</i>

617
00:25:02,288 --> 00:25:03,748
I'm gonna have to have you

618
00:25:03,832 --> 00:25:06,542
read the <i>Times</i> to me.

619
00:25:06,626 --> 00:25:07,835
Mmm.

620
00:25:09,711 --> 00:25:14,174
Yesterday's was better. Susie?

621
00:25:14,258 --> 00:25:15,300
Yes, Sophie?

622
00:25:15,384 --> 00:25:17,344
[SIGHS] My Jell-O was disappointing.

623
00:25:17,428 --> 00:25:19,512
Okay, Sophie, you have
to take a deep breath.

624
00:25:19,596 --> 00:25:21,431
-[INHALES]
<i>-Now listen to me very closely.</i>

625
00:25:21,515 --> 00:25:22,599
Ugh…

626
00:25:22,683 --> 00:25:25,477
This is what you wanted,
to be on Broadway

627
00:25:25,561 --> 00:25:27,394
and prove you are a serious actress.

628
00:25:27,478 --> 00:25:29,063
This is what you came to me for.

629
00:25:29,147 --> 00:25:31,231
So now you have to take
the cork out of your ass,

630
00:25:31,315 --> 00:25:32,691
you have to open your fucking ears,

631
00:25:32,775 --> 00:25:33,901
swallow the disappointing Jell-O,

632
00:25:33,985 --> 00:25:36,028
and go out there and do the work.

633
00:25:36,112 --> 00:25:39,156
You show those assholes you
are right and they are wrong,

634
00:25:39,240 --> 00:25:41,450
and then you can go to the
Tonys and completely forget

635
00:25:41,534 --> 00:25:42,743
to thank me in your acceptance speech.

636
00:25:42,827 --> 00:25:44,370
I will forget to thank you.

637
00:25:44,454 --> 00:25:46,704
You will be great. Gavin will be great.

638
00:25:46,788 --> 00:25:48,498
You will make Gavin great.

639
00:25:48,582 --> 00:25:50,875
I will make him great, won't I?

640
00:25:50,959 --> 00:25:52,251
Put that on your plate.

641
00:25:52,335 --> 00:25:54,754
All right. I'll eat the Jell-O.

642
00:25:54,838 --> 00:25:56,423
That-a girl.

643
00:25:58,341 --> 00:26:00,552
Really getting the hang of this shit.

644
00:26:03,762 --> 00:26:05,764
-[PHONE RINGING]
-[SUSIE WHISTLING]

645
00:26:09,727 --> 00:26:10,852
Hello?

646
00:26:10,936 --> 00:26:12,896
Did you tell Sophie she
would make me better?

647
00:26:12,980 --> 00:26:14,314
What? God, no.

648
00:26:14,398 --> 00:26:16,942
I… I said she'd be made better by you.

649
00:26:17,026 --> 00:26:19,069
Oh. Well, all right then.

650
00:26:19,153 --> 00:26:20,695
But did you know that she wants

651
00:26:20,779 --> 00:26:22,530
-her dogs in the play?
-I did not.

652
00:26:22,614 --> 00:26:24,375
Did you know that she
wants them to have billing?

653
00:26:24,459 --> 00:26:24,865
I did not.

654
00:26:24,949 --> 00:26:27,118
-With a box around their names?
-Did not know that either.

655
00:26:27,202 --> 00:26:29,078
She's impossible to deal
with, did you know that?

656
00:26:29,162 --> 00:26:30,955
-Taking the Fifth.
<i>-I have to say</i>

657
00:26:31,039 --> 00:26:32,832
<i>that in all my years in this business,</i>

658
00:26:32,916 --> 00:26:35,501
I've worked with every drunken,
drug-addled piece of work

659
00:26:35,585 --> 00:26:38,587
in a dress, male or female,
and I have never, ever met

660
00:26:38,671 --> 00:26:41,131
anyone so completely lacking in sanity.

661
00:26:41,215 --> 00:26:42,632
Yeah, I think it feels that way now

662
00:26:42,716 --> 00:26:43,842
'cause you're in the thick of it.

663
00:26:43,926 --> 00:26:45,301
I did <i>Midsummer Night's Dream</i>

664
00:26:45,385 --> 00:26:48,012
where Titania killed Oberon
with a letter opener onstage,

665
00:26:48,096 --> 00:26:50,306
and that woman I would work
with again over Sophie Lennon.

666
00:26:50,390 --> 00:26:52,684
Look, Gavin, her craziness,
if that's what you call it…

667
00:26:52,768 --> 00:26:54,310
It is exactly what I call it.

668
00:26:54,394 --> 00:26:57,063
Her craziness is also her brilliance,

669
00:26:57,147 --> 00:27:00,649
and her brilliance
manifests itself in craziness.

670
00:27:00,733 --> 00:27:02,526
And the real problem
here is that her brilliance

671
00:27:02,610 --> 00:27:03,944
mixed with your brilliance,

672
00:27:04,028 --> 00:27:06,029
well, it's almost too much
brilliance for one production.

673
00:27:06,113 --> 00:27:09,408
Almost.
But there is an even bigger chance

674
00:27:09,492 --> 00:27:13,745
that the brilliance of you
causing the brilliance of her

675
00:27:13,829 --> 00:27:16,540
will stun New York audiences,
bringing them to their knees,

676
00:27:16,624 --> 00:27:18,249
and make your performance
one of those performances

677
00:27:18,333 --> 00:27:21,210
people talk about forever,
like Gielgud's <i>Hamlet.</i>

678
00:27:21,294 --> 00:27:22,420
Oh.

679
00:27:22,504 --> 00:27:24,380
<i>Well, when you put it like that</i>

680
00:27:24,464 --> 00:27:26,299
-[DOGS BARKING]
-[GROANS]

681
00:27:26,383 --> 00:27:28,759
I have to go, my costars are here.

682
00:27:28,843 --> 00:27:32,305
Keep calm and carry on, pal.

683
00:27:32,389 --> 00:27:35,016
-Let me guess. Sophie?
-Gavin.

684
00:27:35,100 --> 00:27:37,517
-About Sophie?
-Where'd you get the grub?

685
00:27:37,601 --> 00:27:38,935
Leftovers from Shy.

686
00:27:39,019 --> 00:27:40,729
God, fucking love rich people food.

687
00:27:40,813 --> 00:27:42,147
He has this beautiful sailboat.

688
00:27:42,231 --> 00:27:44,649
It gave me the perfect chance
to finally wear the boating outfit

689
00:27:44,733 --> 00:27:46,276
-I brought on tour.
-Oh, thank God.

690
00:27:46,360 --> 00:27:47,777
I was getting worried.

691
00:27:47,861 --> 00:27:52,491
You know, Shy's a complicated
man, but I think he likes me.

692
00:27:52,575 --> 00:27:54,950
Yeah? How much?

693
00:27:55,034 --> 00:27:59,121
We're becoming friends.
I have a calming effect on him.

694
00:27:59,205 --> 00:28:00,873
I don't like you on a boat.

695
00:28:00,957 --> 00:28:02,917
-Why not?
-Boats sink.

696
00:28:03,001 --> 00:28:05,211
But they mostly don't, and
that's what makes them boats.

697
00:28:05,295 --> 00:28:07,463
They get torpedoed.
They hit icebergs. No boats.

698
00:28:07,547 --> 00:28:10,799
No bikes.
I don't want you riding on or in anything.

699
00:28:10,883 --> 00:28:12,926
Just sit quietly and read a Bible,

700
00:28:13,010 --> 00:28:14,511
and no New Testament.

701
00:28:16,513 --> 00:28:19,641
Yes, Reggie. I'm gonna take a shower.

702
00:28:19,725 --> 00:28:21,684
I don't know what that
Reggie crack meant,

703
00:28:21,768 --> 00:28:25,522
but this is one hell of a sandwich.
It's so lean.

704
00:28:27,566 --> 00:28:30,068
MIDGE: This is actually
Shy's favorite room to play.

705
00:28:30,152 --> 00:28:32,110
His lucky theater.

706
00:28:32,194 --> 00:28:34,112
-Did you hear that, Mama?
-Hear what?

707
00:28:34,196 --> 00:28:36,281
That this is Shy's
favorite room to perform in.

708
00:28:36,365 --> 00:28:37,491
Perform what?

709
00:28:37,575 --> 00:28:39,618
I think dinner after the
show was a bad idea.

710
00:28:39,702 --> 00:28:41,703
But drinking before was genius.

711
00:28:41,787 --> 00:28:43,789
Oh, excuse me,
waiter, I'd like a martini.

712
00:28:43,873 --> 00:28:45,832
There's one in your hand, Mama.

713
00:28:45,916 --> 00:28:48,753
Parker. Parker, these are…

714
00:28:50,670 --> 00:28:54,006
A martini with olives, but the
martini's the important part.

715
00:28:54,090 --> 00:28:56,592
Mama, you can order at the table.
Control your woman.

716
00:28:56,676 --> 00:28:59,512
Says my daughter before
she performs her comedy.

717
00:28:59,596 --> 00:29:01,347
Let's try this again.

718
00:29:01,431 --> 00:29:04,267
As I was saying, Parker,
these are my parents.

719
00:29:04,351 --> 00:29:06,561
-Abe and Rose Weissman.
-Hello, Parker.

720
00:29:06,645 --> 00:29:09,479
-I ordered a martini. I want it.
